Just - that's - we were out at six I'm telling you and - ken when we were younger of course he carried on. Six o'clock, he'd be away by maybe half past - a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7291225\charrsid9768143 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 ways - he was always early - going to his work. He'd always, and that's what - he used to rub 
into us. Always be in time for your work. Always be there on the dot you know. But then he just had that routine of working and that, and - as I say, at the end of Suspension Bridge, meeting and they would have a wee blether and then away to their work. T
hen - home. Got his breakfast, away back again, dinner time night away his walk and then bed. That's all. He never - he never, I mean -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8206157 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 When you were at the school what time would you get up for your breakfast then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1604703 JR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 Oh I wouldnae say I was ken a 
