 used to calling him that, because ken they were in the Territorial Band and - you ken, the old ones and they were all, ken and this is the way they talked. But I went and - then - here, the next thing was the - Reid the baker. And that was just - it was 
a
 shop, I don't know whether it's still there or no, they tell me half of the buildings are down, I wouldnae ken you ken, I'll say, so and so. Well there's no such a building there now. Oh well it was there you ken when - but it was just across from Brooms
 
Road. And of course here Reid the baker. Of course - I says, oh certainly. Well Reid the baker, it wasnae that I'd that much to do there. I had more for Wyllie the baker ken, I mean - going away along yon Middle Street with two - baskets of rolls and - th
e
n pay on the dot, cash, credit and everything, I had my wee book, to write everything down you know. But Reid wasnae so bad, it was just wee messages. And I went to this Miss Fenwick. She's a high class confectioner and - and her shop was just across from
 
Loreburn Street. Aye, whether it's there or no either. I just crossed over there so - here I used to for Reids - yeast like. Wyllie the baker used to get bags, but Reid the baker, ken, he was just a wee - smaller. And - you ken maybe going for four ounces
 
or wot like that. So here Miss Fenwick - this day she says to me - would I - would I mind, ken, like - just, ken, an odd message or two. Silly me again. I says, certainly. Now I had them three shops. I done it then. I can hardly think myself and that, I s
i
t here and often wonder how I did it, and I - I don't know. I used to call into Reid the bakers first. Coming out of school, like, St Michael Street school I went to. I'd call in and see if there were any messages. Well, maybe there were nothing. Then fro
