Oh it was more like something like that you kwn, like well - maybe - if it was now - maybe they would get called that. But he was that kind of - ken what I mean.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8206157 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 He was interested in politics then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1604703 JR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 Well sometimes - I dinna ken whether - they us
ed to be surprised at him - being, ken, a workman - and that was years ago where they - you ken, there were only two parties. There were - what we called Tory - and Liberals. Duncan was the Tory. And - and Gullane was the Liberal. And I can always mind ab
o
ut, ken the two cards like just like what you get yet, and there was Dundan, that was him - from Newlands. This is one of the - one of the older ones, ken, I dinna ken whether the - the family's still continues or no but - it'd be one of the older ones li
k
e. Then. But he was for the Tories, we called the Tory. And old Gullane as they called him - was for Liberal. Well the working class and that was more - on - for the Liberal - then. And her of course I can and that this day, and of course - ken, at the sc
h
ool like, and of course this Ethel Murphy I run about with too, and she said - she was saying about, ken, like - did - your mother get - ken - gullane and - and Duncan's - photo? And I says - aye. Who does your father vote for? Just you ken naturally, any
b
ody would say - I says, oh I couldna tell you, I couldna tell you who he votes for, but I says, anyway, I says, I ken - he took gullane's photo - now, I can mind of that, and he tore it into; and into the fire. Oh, she said, Jenny, dinna tell me, she says
,
 that your father returns a Tory. And of course I wasna interested in them things then. I says - I didna know - I says, oh well, I says, that's what my father did. I says, and Duncan's photo's up on the - the old mantel. I said, Duncan's - he put Duncan's
 
photo up on the mantelpiece, and old Gullane was torn into - bits. Now I can mind of that. And Ethel thought - oh, she said, mercy, I never thought for one minute Jenny - mercy me, they're all I ken more for - ken - Gullane, and it used to be vote, vote, 
vote for gullane and that you ken like.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8206157 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 Did they have unions in the mills in those days? Were the weavers and the workers like your father in a union?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1604703 JR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 Well - it - it did come and that, ken, a union - cropped up. But - I canna just mind when it was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8206157 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 Would your father be interested in that sort of thing?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1604703 JR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 
And - he was - wasna interested in - anything like that at all, you ken what I mean, he just - wasnae - but I can mind and that of - this - union, and it just had started. And I mind - t
he meetings was held - held in the Labour Hall. I can always mind of that. But anyway, here they're coming out on strike.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8206157 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 When would that be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1604703 JR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 But I was - oh well - when I was in the mill, weaving. And I canna just exactly say how old I was but a
nyway - here it was going to be - a strike. Well, here they picked me, and ken, you know one or two of the younger ones. We were to be the pickets. And that of course, when I went home that night - you ken, at tea time and that, as usual he's - sitting yo
u
 ken at side of me so - he was saying like - so I says - oh, I says - I'm going to the - the Hall. I says, I'm a picket father, I says and naming the other three, I says, we're going to - and we've got to keep them out, keep them you ken. And that was eno
ugh again. And he dared me to go. He dared me to go to that - but anyway, by the time went on it was all settled by midnight. And I didna need to have gone, but he wasnae even - he wouldna even have let me - he wouldn't have let me gone.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8206157 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 You were saying that your sister died when she was quite young, when she was nine?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1604703 JR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 Nine, aye, Jeannie died, aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8206157 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 Can you remember much about her funeral? Or can you remember anybody else's funeral that you noticed when you were a wee girl?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1604703 JR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 Oh well, to tell you the truth you k}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11692283\charrsid9768143 no}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 
w, there were - lots of - of - like funerals and that, of course you never - thingummyjigged or gave - gave them a thought then. But - wee - wee Jeannie I - I didna ken, I can just always mind of the - she had a wee white coffin an
d then - you ken, it - it - seemed to - you ken, away it went. You ken, when I - now think and that like - it must have been the day she was - buried, and I - and I nearly broke my heart, for all I kenned, and I kenned she was there, but - I canna say tha
t - I really - can mind.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8206157 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 You don't remember getting mourning clothes and that sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1604703 JR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 
Well I think it was - it was - in fact, ken, when I think - a wee - I think it was a wee black - frock, and there were high - wore hats, and you called t
hem motor caps, you ken, they were just a - oh in fact I've seen the hat in there, I said to Irene too, I says, that's what I call a motor cap, that's what I'm talking about then - oh - years ago, you called them motor, just a flat thing you ken.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8206157 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 Did it have a veil on it to h}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11692283\charrsid9768143 o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 ld it on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1604703 JR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 
Oh no, just - slipped it on to your head, you ken like and that, I can always mind of that. But it was - you called them motor caps. I don't ken what it was for and that but I can always mind of that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8206157 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 But you weren't actually at your wee sister's funeral then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1604703 JR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 Oh no, no, I wouldna - you ken, I dinna - couldna say that I can mind her even. I cann mind her even being, ken, took out of the house.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8206157 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 Did you remember anybody else's funeral then? Maybe your grandparents or even somebody in the street that maybe everybody went to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1604703 JR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 
Well tell you the truth and that, even - you ken, funerals even at the present day, they dinna, ken, appeal to me. It's - it's just I would rather not - even my sister in Broo
ms Road, well I wasnae able - to, ken, to have gone, but even - ken, I sit and I many a time think here to - I would rather - and even Johnny up the road, like my brother that died last year, the year before, I mean, even - I wasna there either. But I thi
nk I would rather just - think on them as I last seen them ken like. I - I - I mean - I just dinna ken, I just dinna -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8206157 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 You said your mother used to take you to visit your granny?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1604703 JR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 Oh aye, if my mother - if we'd a - if she was missing too that's al
ways what - we would go to her up at 50 High Street. We were all for my granny like and that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8206157 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 She visited there quite a lot then did she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1604703 JR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 Oh aye, aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8206157 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 Would you go up and visit your granny without your mother too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1604703 JR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 Oh aye, oh were all 
- and then I started ken when I got older - ken, a wee bit older and that I - even - joined the church like and - was younger at joining churches then, I dinna think they - they bother now much but - anyway I used to, ken, in the - Communion come round, w
e
ll ken the morning service. I would - I would have rather have went the morning service. But anyway, here of course my granny - poor old soul, she couldna - so - I used to, ken, wait 'til an afternoon, three o'clock like, and used to get up for her and th
en - and then I hunted the - in fact when I go now they've to hunt hymns for me you kn}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14568195\charrsid9768143 ow}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 
, with them specs I cannae - they've to thingummyjig the hymns for me. But I used to hunt them for my granny, and nae bother. But I've no thingummyjigged the - I havena 
been at Communion for - a few times and that but I - I just tell the minister and - and in fact they - they - they dinna even - that's one thing about the chapel and that, they - they - I dinna ken whether churches are the same, but that's one thing about
 
the chapel and that with their - Communion and that. I think - I think anyway and that that - when they ken I'm no able, do you no think that it's their place to - to give me Communion? I mean, they know that I'm no - and I'm going to put it to the elder,
 the - Midsummer - Communion - I'm going to say to him - because our - our minister's retired now like and that like and that, anyway I'm going to put it to him and -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8206157 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 Did you ever go and visit your other granny?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1604703 JR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 Oh, never mind her. Didna know if she was dead, I didna ken. Oh, I didna ken - oh I didna ken nothing about - her at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8206157 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 Did you ever go visiting anybody else with your mother then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1604703 JR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 Oh I think there were ken some of her own old - pals and that too ken like. Used to, ken, follow you - on like and that with her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8206157 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 Did you ever go out with your father at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1604703 JR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 Nowhere. He never went anywhere, he never even went to church, never mind anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8206157 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 Usually it was the done thing for families to go for a walk on Sunday afternoons?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1604703 JR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 
Not him. Oh no, never - couldnae - say that he ever - thingummyjigged or himself or took us out or anything. No like my man, it be just a case of I'll just get them ready and ken we'd all go away out together, and - and then of course there wer
e a big family of Bob's like, we'd plenty of bits to go, go away visit with my side, where - we hadna many friends at all. Because on both sides our own boy and lassied I telled you and that, that - there werenae - but my father never - oh no, as I tell y
ou, all he did was - that was - he'd just - come home, get dinner then - and away and that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8206157 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 What about holidays? You wouldn't all get away together for a summer holiday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1604703 JR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 Oh no, never. Never. In fact - I can mind and that our Jessie - and that, my
 older sister like, and - every summer holiday - Locharbriggs. Well I think this old woman, ken she kept house to the - the - I - I can picture it ken, getting off - off the train mind, and get down this - steep brae, and the house was at the bottom. And 
I
 - I think he was a joiner, but this body, she kept house to him and I think she must have - my father and her must have been related someway, we called her Auntie Mary anyway, I ken that much. Mary Heggar. We called her - Auntie Mary but I think she was 
related to my father. But our Jessie and that - every year - her summer holidays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8206157 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 Just Jessie?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1604703 JR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 
She went there and spent her summer holidays, and I'd be here running my messages as usual, just the same as what I did when I was at the school. And 
- and you had a wee bit time, well - you got a wee bit time to enjoy yourself and so forth, but anyway, when our Jessie, ken, this is now when she was left the school, and go to work, so it was a case of - of - Jennet'll go her summer holidays now perhaps
.
 And when I think many a time Bob and I had a laugh at it. When I think on getting my case packed, and going to the station, get the train. You sat down in the train, you were nae sooner sat down - 'til you're out. And then you'd this big brae and - the j
o
iner's shop ken now - well, it was the house and - and a joiner's shop, and - maybe it's no there now, God knows, but here - down there. So here, oh my God, on the other side of the house and there were a boy and, ken - he'd just be something like myself,
 
maybe older as me but he stood at the door and he were doing - at me. And used to stand watching, and he carried on. So anyway I went in to - Auntie Mary's as we called her, I said to her I said, that boy over there, I says, is putting his tongue out at m
e
. Auntie Mary. I says - oh she said - and I'm no touching - I'm no bothering him. Oh, she says, never need him, he's no just, you ken, never heed him. And I says, I didna like that. Oh - well - oh I've got to suffer six weeks here. It'll drive me nuts. So
 
this day she says to me - going into the joiner's shop Jennet and - and get a bit of wood, break it up for the fire. And it was seemingly an old bit of wood I was to get. But Janet went in - I went into the joiner's shop and I got a nice new bit of timber
 
and I broke it up. And then I got another box and - thinking I was doing - oh my God, here she goon to me, I had broke her ash bucket up too, her box, ken for the ashes. I - oh my, she was in a hack of a state, and she says - that was my - I says, well yo
u
 wanted a bit of firewood didn't you, I says, well that's all I could get and that wee bit of new stuff, I says, well I thought it would make it up. Oh, it nearly broke - so I says to her I says, I'm going home on Saturday, I says, I couldnae stick this. 
A
nd that was a week, and I says, my God, never again. And I've walked to Locahrbriggs many a time, you ken, since then. But when I think on it, ken, and - and I mind this Agnes Murphy I ran mates with, too, she came to the station to see me off. I was neve
r
 as thankful to get - back. And that was my, you ken, and still our Jessie and that now - just - must have been - oh Jessie enjoyed - every minute of it. But heavens it nearly drove me crackers. There were nobody bar that boy, ken, and standing putting hi
s tongue out. There were nae weans you ken to play with or anything like that. Oh I was just by myself, o this is terrible you ken.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8206157 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 What about going away for the day, did you ever go away on a jaunt for the day? Everybody together?
\par }\pard\plain \ltrpar\s15\qj \fi-490\li518\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin518\itap0\pararsid8206157 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs24\lang2057\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1033 {
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1604703 JR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 Oh I can only 
mind when, you ken the likes to the mothers and all that, it was only once in a while, you ken, the likes of Mrs Murphy, Mrs Morley, and the other families you see ken they were all big families. And just once in a while - Glencaple, the Old Queays we cal
l
ed it. And here of course they would make up their mind, and they were going to take us all for an outing, to the Old Quay, and of course we thought it was great, and it was the wagonettes, you ken, with the old horse, and this is what we were - here ther
e
 were this Fisher, and there were Clark, and the Clarkes - ken were awfully nice, we used to say old Fisher you ken, it was - all the trade he wanted, but this - I can mind? I - I dinna ken whether Clarks ken have any conveyance now but they were awfully 
n
ice like and the father ken was a nice man, I expect the sons all followed, and maybe grandsons too, but this Fisher, well the - the wagoneetes as we called them, it was the - at Ninth Place we got them. And this Fisher used to, ken, any Sunday or nice da
y, and they would be standing and ken saying, come in, to get his - wagonette ful, and Mr Clarke's standing and that nice a man but anyway we used to ignore him, but this was our outing, and away we used to go. To the Quay. It was only three}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14568195\charrsid9768143  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 pence each.
