e works at McGeorges factory and Rachel and I too, well her father had a butchers shop in Queensberry Street, and I can mind her mother too, used to, ken, be in the shop. Anyway Rachel and I was great, and then this old Houston. There's an Houston a butch
e
r ken up the Greenbrae there. Well, there's - a brother, Rachel married Albert. And do you know this, Rachel and him - was boy and lassie sweethearts as you call them. Rachel and him, from they were at the - from they were - and Rachel had - and then of c
o
urse when they grew older - they got married. And then they went away abroad and I never - never - I've - often - ken would like to - to learn about them. Ken, I didna get up the butchers there like - like - well I dinna - but Irene, I mean - she goes to 
t
he butcher in Queen Street, but - if I'd been thing - up there, I would certainly ask - ken like - Bert, well, we used to call him Kid Houston, but - I would like to ken, ask about Rachel and Albert. And many a time I picture Rachel ken. And oh, ken that,
 oh she was really - I canna say that I ever fought with any lassie, ken.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8206157 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 
I suppose if there were a lot of children in the street, if you weren't agreeing very well with one there would always be somebody else to play with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1604703 JR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 Well I canna - aye, well I canna re - mind, I - I ken, fighting with - or any of them fighting.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8206157 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 What was it like at the school then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1604703 JR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 It was just the same, because the simple - it was the same ken crowd. That we were brought up with, as we went to school, as I tell yo
u and that at the Sunday school - on a Sunday, I was Nettie. Monday morning at the day school - Jennie. Now was that - I don't know, and Miss - this - Miss Smith - that was the - Sunday school teacher like up the stair, she - started calling me Nettie, an
d
 there were only two, and that nephew over there, and his brother, and I get nothing else but Aunt Nettie yet from them, even her - ken it's always Launt Nettie. But I were Jennie at the day school. We Jennie Millar you ken, we were always called wee, for
 I seemed to be the wee one amongst them all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8206157 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 Were most of the youngsters that were at school with you from the same sort of background, you all came from the same sort of houses did you?

