With Wyllie? Oh aye, that - it - yes, that's what I say too you see, I - I went to - I had to - I worked there about - I said to Mrs Willie at the time I says - in fact that morning I made my mind up and I've got my basket, and of course when I come to t
he shop window, you ken, I was sick and I says - oh Jenny or Annie's in, and ken, well Annie Wyllie herself, she was in the factory, this is the youngest Wyllie lassie, and she was in the factory on a silk frame, like silk gloves away at the bottom of the
 
shop, and here - I thought and that too, I says, well, ken - when I left like - Annie wasna pleased because she had to leave the job and go into the shop and she - oh she wasnae pleased. She says, oh Jenny I thought you would ken, I says, oh well, I says 
-
 I don't know, I says, but I - I'm going to do it anyway. But anyway, that morning and here when I got to the shop, here it's Mrs Wyllie herself. Even I was feared - I werena feared for the woman, I was feared to tell her. And she said, ken how you get ki
n
d of worked up and that - and - I says - oh, I says, I'm leave - I'm leaving, Mrs Wyllie. And of course she just, eeh, what do you mean Jenny? I says, Johnny Marshall's got me a job in the factory, so, I says, I'm going in there. So here of course all tha
t
 Annie had to leave, but I used to go and help them out, and especially on Saturday night and they were open to midnight, and I scrubbed that old floor, but I used to go round to Brooke Street and sleep instead of going home like and that, ken, midnight a
nd that and there we were trailing away around, shop was even open to - about twelve o'clock and that but I had to scrub all that shop out. And here - I got two and six for it. For a Saturday - two and six, and I got two and six for the whole week. And -

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8206157 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 What sort of money were you paid in the factory, was it all that much better?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1604703 JR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 
Aye, aye well it was up to yourself like and that, ken it was like piecework. And it was - the job I went into was like - pulling gloves, ken, they were a roll and you 
pulled the cotton to separate, like there were - the frames for - handing gloves like, they used to have the cuffs. There was a frame for cuffs, and then what you called the hand - hand - handers like, they put the cuff on and made - but this was off the 
s
team frames and you ken the glove was all in one one, bar the fingers like, and this cotton, and you'd to take the cotton and then - reel round the top, the cuff like and pull away, and it was - and then - after that you'd to mark them. Ken, there were me
n, outside and that and - different - bits of wool lie, red, blue and whatever you ken the size was, and - bundle them up, like in dozens. Penny a dozen. A penny a - a penny -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8206157 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 You'd have to work hard to make any money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1604703 JR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 I did, and my - believe me 
I never went home unless I'd two pound, and that was - I'll guarantee my ma and that could never - but I used to even take gloves home and pull them too. I used to take them home just to make, you ken, and if I'd been a penny off the - two pound I used to
 put a penny if I had a penny in my pocket, put it onto it. I wouldna give my ma you ken.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8206157 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 Did your mother give you back some of that for spending yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1604703 JR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid921314\charrsid9768143 Well I used to get half a crown. But then I was buying my own clothes and everything then too. But -
